exam_name: The Princeton Review - Digital SAT Advanced Online Test - English - Module 2 - Hard
subject: English
stimulus: Immediately following the Big Bang, the lightest elements, such as lithium, helium, and hydrogen, were produced. Other, heavier elements—such as iron—were formed over time in the cores of stars. The origin of these heavier elements has perplexed scientists for decades. It has been theorized that the rapid absorption of neutrons (known as r-process) releases these heavier elements into space. Following a collision of two dead stars, an event that involves extremely rapid rates of neutron absorption, astrophysicist Darach Watson and colleagues expected to observe the release of at least some of the heavier elements. They were surprised, however, to detect the presence of only strontium, one of the lightest heavy elements in existence.
question_stem: Which choice best describes the overall structure of the text?

answer_choices.A: It presents a hypothesis about a phenomenon, shares the results of a recent observation of that phenomenon, and then confirms the hypothesis.
answer_choices.B: It puts forth a new hypothesis about a currently debated scientific topic, discusses the methodology of an experiment intended to test the hypothesis, and then disproves the hypothesis.
answer_choices.C: It introduces a scientific question, discusses scientists’ assumptions about it, and then shows how one team was surprised by the results of an event that challenged the previous assumptions.
answer_choices.D: It calls into question a previously propagated theory about the creation of the universe, lists the objections to the theory, and then offers a competing theory.

exam_name: The Princeton Review - Digital SAT Advanced Online Test - English - Module 2 - Hard
subject: English
stimulus:
The following text is adapted from Thomas Mann’s 1924 novel The Magic Mountain. In the novel, protagonist Hans Castorp visits his cousin, who has tuberculosis, at a sanatorium in the Swiss mountains.

The pity the well person felt for the sick—a pity that almost amounted to awe, because the well person could not imagine how he himself could possibly bear such suffering—was very greatly exaggerated. The sick person had no real right to it. It was, in fact, the result of an error in thinking, a sort of hallucination; in that the well man attributed to the sick his own emotional equipment, and imagined that the sick man was, as it were, a well man who had to bear the agonies of a sick one—than which nothing was further from the truth.
question_stem: Which choice describes the function of the underlined portion in the text as a whole?

answer_choices.A: It contradicts the generally accepted belief that healthy people are unable to imagine the suffering of those who are terminally ill.
answer_choices.B: It questions the assertion that tuberculosis is necessarily a terminal disease and declares that such claims are greatly exaggerated.
answer_choices.C: It elaborates upon an emotion felt by a well person toward a sick person that may not be as strongly felt as conventionally believed.
answer_choices.D: It suggests that the well person has no real right to offer the sick person emotional comfort and cannot alleviate the suffering of the ill.

exam_name: The Princeton Review - Digital SAT Advanced Online Test - English - Module 2 - Hard
subject: English
stimulus:
Text 1

Some scholars argue that because humans were likely at least in part responsible for the extinction of the woolly mammoth, scientists should try to bring this species back. Geneticist George Church has made 15 genetic alterations to elephant genes to render them more mammoth-like. Church and others argue that reintroducing the mammoth could improve the biodiversity of arctic ecosystems that have been impacted by the effects of climate change.

Text 2

Paleobiologist Tori Herridge notes that Asian elephants and mammoths are no more related than are chimpanzees and humans and that a surrogate elephant mother could face serious health challenges were a genetically altered elephant embryo to be implanted inside her. She further contends that there are more straightforward ways to combat climate change and adds that bringing back species could reintroduce to the world diseases that would threaten livestock or humans.
question_stem: Based on the texts, how would the author of Text 2 most likely respond to the claim in the underlined sentence of Text 1?

answer_choices.A: By claiming that distantly related species may eventually grow closer genetically without human intervention
answer_choices.B: By noting that there are significant consequences to any attempt to reintroduce the wooly mammoth
answer_choices.C: By condemning the previous work done in genetic modification for focusing on the revival of only a single species
answer_choices.D: By asserting that most species are not able to adapt to changes in the climate of their ecosystem

exam_name: The Princeton Review - Digital SAT Advanced Online Test - English - Module 2 - Hard
subject: English
stimulus: Organisms usually require a brain and nervous system to coordinate their movements. According to a study led by biochemist Wallace Marshall, though, a single-celled organism called Euplotes eurystomus can apparently walk using a simple, mechanical processor. The protozoan E. eurystomus has 14 clusters of cilia, which are hair-like structures controlled by a series of internal connections. Disruptions in these connections can cause malfunctions, such as circular movements rather than the intended linear direction observed under normal conditions.
question_stem: It can most reasonably be inferred from the text that the finding about Euplotes eurystomus was important for which reason?

answer_choices.A: It suggested that single-celled organisms such as E. eurystomus actually do have nervous systems and simple brains.
answer_choices.B: It rejected a previously held notion that protozoa move by means of a rudimentary processor.
answer_choices.C: It confirmed previous studies that found protozoa incapable of coordinated movement.
answer_choices.D: It demonstrated that certain organisms may not, as was previously thought, need a brain to generate deliberate locomotion.

exam_name: The Princeton Review - Digital SAT Advanced Online Test - English - Module 2 - Hard
subject: English
stimulus: To assist other researchers in estimating liquid drainage times, physicist Fadhilah Mohd Sakri and colleagues analyzed a 2011 study that measured the actual or estimated drainage time during three separate 20-second intervals during the time that it took for water to drain from a tank. The 2011 team used three different methods of measurement: an experiment that featured a physical tank filled with water, a theoretical analysis that focused on the known properties of water movement, and a numerical analysis that accounted for both the water in the tank as well as the air present in both the tank and the drainpipe. After reviewing this data, Sakri and colleagues determined that the theoretical analysis may not be as accurate for future estimations as the numerical analysis will be.
question_stem: Which choice best describes data from the graph that support Sakri and his colleagues’ conclusion?

answer_choices.A: At the second and third intervals, the estimated water height predicted by the theoretical analysis was lower than the actual water height observed during the experimental analysis.
answer_choices.B: At the second interval, the estimated water height predicted by the theoretical analysis was lower than the actual water height observed during the experimental analysis, but at the third interval, the actual water height observed during the experimental analysis was higher than the estimated water height predicted by the numerical analysis.
answer_choices.C: At the first interval, the estimated water height predicted by the theoretical analysis was lower than both the actual water height observed during the experimental analysis and the estimated water height predicted by the numerical analysis.
answer_choices.D: At all three intervals, the estimated water height predicted by the theoretical analysis was not as close to the actual water height observed during the experimental analysis as the numerical analysis was.

exam_name: The Princeton Review - Digital SAT Advanced Online Test - English - Module 2 - Hard
subject: English
stimulus: “Fragment of a Satire on Satire” is an 1880 poem by Percy Bysshe Shelley. The poem focuses on the dangers of satire as the speaker notes the emotional damage satirical comments can cause while also expressing his distaste for those who make them, writing ________
question_stem: Which quotation from “Fragment of a Satire on Satire” most effectively illustrates the claim?

answer_choices.A: “ 'Tis not worth while to prove, as I could, how / From the sweet fountains of our Nature flow / These bitter waters.”
answer_choices.B: “Follow his flight with winged words, and urge / The strokes of the inexorable scourge / Until the heart be naked, till his soul / See the contagion's spots ... foul.”

stimulus: It had been previously believed that an affected individual will experience the highest possibility of COVID-like or Influenza-like symptoms between the ages of 30 and 34, but older individuals must exercise caution as the occurrence of symptomatic incidents is not necessarily reduced with age even with diseases that have been around longer, such as Influenza, as evidenced by the information that ________

answer_choices.C: patients between 35 and 39 years old experienced, on average, more Influenza-like symptomatic incidents than did any other age group experiencing Influenza-like symptoms.

exam_name: The Princeton Review - Digital SAT Advanced Online Test - English - Module 2 - Hard
subject: English
stimulus: Philosopher Lawrence Kohlberg posited six stages of ethical development, focusing particularly on the reasoning capabilities possessed by an individual at each stage rather than the actual choices made. Based on Jean Piaget’s theory of cognitive development, Kohlberg’s theory presents increasingly nuanced ethical perspectives, starting at punishment avoidance (level one) to universal ethical principles (level six). As an illustrative example, Kohlberg offered the theoretical “Heinz dilemma,” in which Heinz’s wife is ill and can be saved only by a newly invented drug. Unable to afford the drug, Heinz steals it. A person solving the dilemma must say whether or not Heinz should have stolen the drug and why. Kohlberg was uninterested in a person’s choice of “yes” or “no,” though, because ________
question_stem: Which choice most logically completes the text?

answer_choices.A: identical responses made by individuals at different stages of ethical development would have been described by Kohlberg as ethically similar unless those responses were affected by external factors, such as the desire to impress others.
answer_choices.B: Kohlberg would have disregarded the concept that the actual decision made by the person is relevant to assessing their reasoning capabilities in order to determine which stage of ethical development the person is in.
answer_choices.C: Kohlberg would have disregarded the concept that the actual decision made by the person can be fairly evaluated given the formal, laboratory nature of the experiment.
answer_choices.D: the individuals observed by Kohlberg during the experiment could not be properly categorized into a stage of ethical development even though participants demonstrated their reasoning capabilities during the explanation of their response choice.

subject: English
stimulus: A recent agricultural study undertaken by scientists in Xinjiang, China, investigated whether the presence of licorice root could boost the number of predators (mainly ladybeetles, but also other arthropods) near cotton crops to reduce aphid populations, which are harmful to the crops. Results from the peak seasons of two consecutive years showed that fields treated with strips of licorice root experienced a 17.5% decrease in aphid density in the first year and a 61.2 % decrease in the second year, compared to control fields. According to these findings, the study’s researchers suggest that the use of licorice root ________
question_stem: Which choice most logically completes the text?

answer_choices.A: can significantly reduce the numbers of aphids harmful to crops, potentially allowing for higher crop yields.
answer_choices.B: increases the density of the aphid populations, leading to reduced crop yields in licorice-treated fields.
answer_choices.C: reduces the numbers of aphids during the first year, though not during the second year.
answer_choices.D: has no significant effect on the numbers of aphids but did lower the numbers of other arthropods.

exam_name: The Princeton Review - Digital SAT Advanced Online Test - English - Module 2 - Hard
subject: English
stimulus:
While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes:

  • The Saffir-Simpson scale classifies hurricanes based on the speed of their maximum sustained
  • A hurricane is classified as Category 4 if its maximum sustained winds are between 130 and 156 miles per hour.
  • A hurricane is classified as Category 5 if its maximum sustained winds are 157 miles per hour or more.
  • Hurricane Norbert had maximum sustained winds of 135 miles per hour.
  • It struck the west coast of Mexico in October of 2008.
question_stem: The student wants to indicate which category Hurricane Norbert belongs in, based on the speed of its winds. Which choice uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?

answer_choices.A: The Saffir-Simpson scale classified Hurricane Norbert according to the speed of its maximum sustained winds.
answer_choices.B: Having maximum sustained winds of 135 miles per hour, Hurricane Norbert was classified as Category 4 by the Saffir-Simpson scale.
answer_choices.C: Hurricane Norbert had maximum sustained winds of 135 miles per hour and struck the west coast of Mexico in October of 2008.
answer_choices.D: According to the Saffir-Simpson scale, which classifies hurricanes such as Hurricane Norbert, Category 4 hurricanes have maximum sustained winds between 130 and 156 miles per hour.

exam_name: The Princeton Review - Digital SAT Advanced Online Test - English - Module 2 - Hard
subject: English
stimulus:
While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes:

  • John Cage was an American experimental music composer.
  • His works were unusual in that they often featured instruments that did not produce their typical sounds.
  • His piece The Wonderful Widow of Eighteen Springs (1942), for voice and piano, requires the piano to remain closed.
  • In the piece, the pianist produces percussive sounds by manually striking different parts of the piano.
  • Cage’s piece 4’33 (1952), for any instrument or instruments, is composed of three movements.
  • In the piece, the instruments produce no sound at all.
question_stem: The student wants to emphasize a similarity between the two pieces. Which choice uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?

answer_choices.A: Both The Wonderful Widow of Eighteen Springs and 4’33 feature instruments that don’t produce their typical sounds.
answer_choices.B: Cage composed The Wonderful Widow of Eighteen Springs in 1942 and 4’33 in 1952.
answer_choices.C: In The Wonderful Widow of Eighteen Springs, the pianist produces sounds by manually striking a closed piano, while in 4’33, the instruments produce no sound at all.
answer_choices.D: Cage’s 4’33 is composed of three movements in which the instruments produce no sound at all.
